# Base Web Application Flowchart

## Mermaid Flowchart Syntax

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Application Entry] --> B{Authentication}
    B -->|New User| C[Registration Page]
    B -->|Existing User| D[Login Page]
    
    C --> C1{Validate Input}
    C1 -->|Valid| C2[Create Account]
    C1 -->|Invalid| C3[Show Errors]
    
    D --> D1{Validate Credentials}
    D1 -->|Success| D2{User Role}
    D1 -->|Failure| D3[Login Error]
    
    D2 -->|Admin| E[Admin Dashboard]
    D2 -->|User| F[User Dashboard]
    
    E --> E1[User Management]
    E --> E2[System Config]
    
    F --> F1[Profile]
    F --> F2[Personal Dashboard]
    
    subgraph Security
        SEC1[JWT Authentication]
        SEC2[Role-Based Access]
    end
    
    subgraph Database
        DB1[MongoDB Atlas]
        DB2[User Collection]
    end
```

## Flowchart Explanation

### Authentication Flow
1. **Entry Point**: Users begin at the application entry
2. **Authentication Paths**:
   - New users go to Registration
   - Existing users go to Login

### Registration Process
- Input validation
- Account creation
- Error handling for invalid inputs

### Login Process
- Credential validation
- Role-based access control
- Error handling for failed logins

### Dashboards
- Admin Dashboard: User management, system configuration
- User Dashboard: Profile, personal insights

### Security Layers
- JWT-based authentication
- Role-based access control

### Database Interaction
- Utilizing MongoDB Atlas
- Dedicated user collection

